D-19?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inhibits protease enzyme with ritonavir boosting levels","Stimulates interferon production","Blocks viral entry into host cells","Inhibits viral RNA-dependent RNA polymerase","Prevents viral membrane fusion"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENirmatrelvir inhibits the main protease (3CL protease) of SARS-CoV-2 with ritonavir boosting\u003C/strong\u003E its levels through cytochrome P450 3A4 inhibition. This prevents the processing of viral polyproteins that are essential for viral replication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulates interferon production\u003C/strong\u003E: while interferons play a role in antiviral immunity, this is not the mechanism by which nirmatrelvir/ritonavir works.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks viral entry into host cells\u003C/strong\u003E: this describes the mechanism of monoclonal antibodies that target the viral spike protein.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits viral RNA-dependent RNA polymerase\u003C/strong\u003E: this is the mechanism by which remdesivir exerts its antiviral effect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrevents viral membrane fusion\u003C/strong\u003E: this mechanism is not utilised by any currently approved COVID-19 antivirals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of nirmatrelvir with ritonavir allows for twice-daily dosing and improved bioavailability of the active antiviral component.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Nirmatrelvir inhibits the main protease of SARS-CoV-2, preventing viral protein processing and replication.","Ritonavir increases nirmatrelvir levels by inhibiting its metabolism through cytochrome P450 3A4.","Remdesivir is a nucleoside analogue that inhibits viral RNA-dependent RNA polymerase."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58982"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17065"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58982","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58982"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-23T22:19:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-23T22:23:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9755"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73513"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"c